Fisheye has been dying recently with the following error in the logs:

{noformat}@400000004a835a7302a05ef4 WARN  - Nested in javax.servlet.ServletException: org.apache.jasper.JasperException: 
/WEB-INF/jsp/crucible/review/monolithic/displayFrxInnerDiv.jsp(1,213) 
PWC6188: The absolute uri: http://java.sun.com/jsp/jstl/core cannot be resolved in either web.xml or the jar files deployed with this application:
@400000004a82272b12dd8954       at org.apache.jasper.compiler.DefaultErrorHandler.jspError(DefaultErrorHandler.java:73)
@400000004a82272b12dd9124       at org.apache.jasper.compiler.ErrorDispatcher.dispatch(ErrorDispatcher.java:359)
@400000004a82272b12dd950c       at org.apache.jasper.compiler.ErrorDispatcher.jspError(ErrorDispatcher.java:153)
{noformat}

When this happens crucible reviews are not viewable. You just get a grey screen. Bouncing FE seems to fix the problems but we need to find out what exactly is happening. 

We have seen a few support cases related to this. Will accumulate them here.

Some projects are more adhoc (the Atlassian RefApp is a good example), where a developer may find themselves hacking on it to fix a problem or implement something without a JIRA issue.  In these cases, things are committed with no issue key, because the developer couldn't be bothered creating an issue just so they can have something to commit against.  This new feature would make that a lot easier.

I propose that we allow the following:

{noformat}
#create [PROJECTKEY] [issuetype] Issue Title [#time|#resolve|#comment etc]
{noformat}

This will create an issue with the given title.  No issue key may be specified on the same line before the #create command.  If the first word after the create command is all capital letters, then this word is checked to see if it's a valid project key.  If it is, the issue is created in that project, if not, or if not specified, it's created in the project the commit was made to.  If the remainder of the message starts with, case insensitive, an issue type, then the issue is created as one of those types.  Otherwise, it's created as the projects default issue type.  The rest of the message, up until the next new line or # command, is considered the issue title.  Any following # commands on the same line are then applied to the newly created issue.
